This antecedent probability of the earlier date is strongly supported by several passages in the second book of the de Divinatione, wherein the writer indicates clearly that his literary activities had suffered a serious interruption through the death of Caesar,² which had given him, as he then supposed, the opportunity and the duty of engaging once more in active political lise, but that before this interruption the series of his philosophical works already included not only the first book of the de Divinatione but also the Cato Maior.⁸
